name: Hot and Bothered
description: This work is part of my series ‚ÄúColor, Balance‚Äù where bodily artifacts removed from fashion photography become the base for paintings I create in Photoshop. I add subtle layers of digital paint and push pixels to blend the figure‚Äôs remnants into the background. I use color as a spatial feature, shifting away the boundary of the body to further blur lines between abstraction and figuration. An aspect of my practice engages the use of computer software that removes all traces of my hand‚Äî the process iterates the disappearance of the physical body on and off the screen. With this work, I aim to express the complexity of 21st-century identity, and the disconnect between the body and those around us. Physical works from this series where shown at my solo exhibition ‚ÄúI Am A Portrait‚Äù at Undercurrent, Brooklyn in January 2020.

name: The Garden City
description: [‚ÄòI will leave you lunch in the fridge, son.‚Äô I saw those teary eyes at the end of the night while we all shared the last food of those days. I sold everything but a desktop computer. My tears fell on the keyboard of an AMD Athlon 2.33 GHz, while from the moistened wall the smell of antiquity arose. It was a rented and very old house in the Garden city, with keys from the colonial time. My days at the art institute were over and I lost my job. The next night with friends I ate delicious bread with coffee. All of them kept talking about our country‚Äôs hyperinflation of 5395%, and I went with a friend to his house to sleep. We were on a high speed highway in the middle of the night thinking about how to cross. Breaking the law was a common thing in that concrete jungle. While listening a few gun detonations from the other side, I said to my friend, 'I am afraid to cross. I am high.' He answered me, ‚ÄòTrust me, I have been more high and I always cross this highway, just follow me.' We survived that day...but my friend was hit by a bus with bullet holes weeks ago. name: Sleeper 2020
description: Interpretation of Salvador Dalis work "Sleeper"(1937). I recreated the figure and the whole environment in 3D software Blender. It is alive and well in this digital medium with a bit dystopian twist of the year 2020.In my work, I choose to rework famous surrealist paintings, because I think this medium of 3d was made for them, and I would like to imagine what, for example, Dali would do with the tools and mediums we have today if he had the chance!

name: Neural Delights #3
description: This work is part of a series of GAN generated images that I created as a contribution for Nick Knight's "Fashion Digital Future" - first shown at Harrods, London in October 2020.In an iterative process I call "Transhancement" I reinterpret catwalk images from 20 years of fashion shows. For this I trained a custom neural network on "The Garden of Earthly Delights" by 16th century painter Hieronymus Bosch. As a result it deliberately misinterprets the data it is given and produces forms and textures that are undoubtedly reminiscent of his aesthetic whilst at the same time introduces surreal shapes and strange compositions.For this series I developed my own custom GAN architecture and training process which attempts to generate a rich variety of textural details whilst at the same time tries not to imitate brush strokes but maintain its own "convolutional" aesthetic.

name: Memento Mori
description: 'Memento Mori' (in Latin) means 'remember (that) you must die'. It serves to remind us of our own mortality, of our failures and victories, to become aware of our (limited) present time, and of the inevitable transformation of life into death. This specific work piece carries a personal reminder to continue living a life of virtue NOW, and not wait. Meditating on your mortality is only depressing if you miss the point. It is in fact, a tool to create priority and meaning, real perspective and urgency. Treat your time here as a gift. Death doesn‚Äôt make life pointless but rather purposeful. A simple reminder, such as this piece of work, can bring us closer to living the life we want. Memento Mori.

name: Sugar: The Silent Killer II
description: This piece highlights an artistic expression of our bodies degradation. Art can be seen in both creation and destruction, art does not judge, unlike its observer. We eat thing which we shouldn't indulge into as often, while it feels very tasty, we know with a guilty sense that no matter what we tell ourselves, the body keeps the score and sooner or later we shall see what we are 'sowing'. A silent and long term killer, you won't even see it coming because it's always with you, by your side. Sugar causes our glucose levels to spike and plummet. An unstable blood sugar can leave you experiencing mood swings, fatigue, and headaches. It also contributes to cravings, which begin the cycle of false hunger and cravings for sweets. It affects the brain much like cocaine and alcohol, according to a brain-scan study from the U.S. National Institute on Drug Abuse. While you probably know that sugars can affect your body composition, they can also mess with your skin by contributing to wrinkles and sagging. After sugar hits your bloodstream, it attaches to proteins. The mix of these proteins with sugar causes the skin to lose elasticity and leads to premature aging. When we‚Äôre under stress, our bodies immediately kick into fight-or-flight mode, releasing large amounts of hormones. Surprisingly, the body has the same chemical response when blood sugar is low. After you eat a sweet snack, stress hormones begin to compensate for the crash by raising your blood sugar. The result? Unexplained anxiousness, irritability, and even shakiness. It increases the risk of obesity, diabetes, and heart disease. Sugar also hides in plain sight. From sucrose, which is table sugar, to high-fructose corn syrup, which is liquid sugar, food producers have come up with a plethora of ways to list this nutrient on labels. This makes it even easier to skim over a long ingredient name in a shopping hurry and inadvertently take in more sugar than you meant to.

name: Sign In
description: "Sign In" is one of my exquisite and early artworks. I have noticed that when presenting a story next to an artwork, it can evoke different feelings and memories in the viewer, while the story holds enough weight to influence that. With this in mind, I choose not to force any story upon the observers, and instead to let them have their very own interpretation and moment. I do believe that part of what makes the art world so beautiful is that everyone can embrace their own sense of perceiving what they see without having to be right or wrong. You do not have to feel something which you are supposed to feel, because whatever you are "supposed" to feel is merely the interpretation of another person or group of people. With love, Kalisto Senna.

name: The Platform
description: This is a style exploration, an attempt to visualize what a personal operating system might actually look/feel like when revealed to others in a transhuman society.  Abstraction is used to convey the truly exotic nature of the deep future, where pattern and intent can be discerned, but the culture and tech are beyond a modern human's comprehension.  Inspired by my ideasthesia, this is also the first piece where I attempted to digitally portray my "timeforms." (2D shapes that change and iterate through time as the 3rd dimension.)  They can visualize states of a system, to reflect on how they changed in the past or to project models into the future.  When creative problem solving, I get the impression of these types of forms, even though I can't fully explain or decode them consciously.On completing this, I really felt that I'd found my voice as an artist.Resolution:  6,000 x 4,500

name: Poppy
description: Presenting a digital reflection of an idea as my gardening mission progresses. A piece from the 'I want to make a garden and yet I am so far from it' series. As my constant explorative excitement continues to absorb bits and pieces of my other plans, I need to create a constructive space for both ends to meet.I want to make a garden and yet I am so far from it is a personal wip I started in early 2020. A part of it is a continuation of my previous subject concerning speculative hybridization combined with the question: "Why do I get emotionally moved from experiencing the richness of anyone's garden?". Because I appreciate the craftsmanship? Or the wild spirited lack or it. It is human nature to travel with eyes around the roots and leaves. To experience it at one's own pace without being told what to feel. I enjoy that charming moment.So what exists amid this nature? The robotica, insect shells, otherly beings, particles. To differentiate a shell from a shell, and a machine form from a machine form, one is meant to be present, to see it freshly, rather than quickly interpreting it and being distracted. A self projection nonetheless.

name: Unveiling Femme Satoshi
description: Little is known about Satoshi Nakamoto, the person. Although often Satoshi is referred to as a he in a singular, that is only for convenience as no one know whether he is an individual, a group, an institution or even, as some may believe, an alien from outer space. There are, however, circumstantial evidences and some revealing statements which may show why he is anonymous and why it may be difficult, if not perhaps impossible, for his identity to be unwillingly known. In all probability Satoshi is a cypherpunk, a group of prescient who‚Äôs who of the computer world who foresaw decades ago the dangers, as well as the benefits, of technology with a primary focus on the near death of privacy that our society now faces. They are and have been at the forefront of an arms race between a government which aims to know more and more and a citizenry which highly values privacy and anonymity. Egold, Liberty Dollar, Liberty Reserve and all other previous attempts at emoney, like Napster, were centrally controlled and shut down by the government for one reason or another. Furthermore, the leaders of these centralized attempts at creating emoney were imprisoned under one law or another, which would have warned anyone familiar with these events that the government was very hostile to any attempts to create emoney.Satoshi was clearly aware of this background as shown by a statement he made in a Bitcointalk thread about a wired article on Bitcoin which paints it as a currency that Wikileaks could adopt to raise funding following a financial blockade by banking institution:Satoshi was clearly aware of this background as shown by a statement he made in a Bitcointalk thread about a wired article on Bitcoin which paints it as a currency that Wikileaks could adopt to raise funding following a financial blockade by banking institution: ‚ÄúIt would have been nice to get this attention in any other context.  WikiLeaks has kicked the hornet‚Äôs nest, and the swarm is headed towards us.‚Äù It is probable, therefore, that the precautions he would have taken to maintain anonymity would have needed to be sufficiently robust to protect from government surveillance, which, even prior to Snowden‚Äôs revelations, was taken to be a fact by the cyberpunks as they believe that ‚Äúinformation does not just want to be free, it longs to be free.  Information expands to fill the available storage space.‚Äù The hacker‚Äôs claim therefore that Satoshi used a ‚Äúprimary gmx under his full name and had aliases set up underneath it‚Äù is simply not credible when Satoshi‚Äôs aim seems to have been from the very beginning to leave no trace of his identity not only to the public, but also to the government.He has succeeded so far and his success has turned him into a hero of the digital age, an incarnation of the principle of privacy which is impossible without anonymity, and into a figure of myth which, like all myths, tells us a truth about today‚Äôs reality through symbolisms and metaphors. Genesis Block is the name of the first block of Bitcoin ever mined‚Äîthus called "Genesis." The Genesis Block forms the foundation of the entire Bitcoin trading system and is the prototype of all other blocks in the blockchain. In 2009, Bitcoin's named developer, Satoshi Nakamoto, created the Genesis Block, which launched the process of Bitcoin trading that's in place today. Perhaps the true gift of the Genesis Block is its legacy of accountability, integrity, and transparency. Because the Genesis Block, also known as Block 0, began the process of trading bitcoin, Bitcoin fans hold the Genesis Block in a kind of cult-like reverence, as they do its creator. Fans are drawn to Bitcoin's arcane construct and idiosyncratic vocabulary with the fervor of one obsessed with a sophisticated arcade game.Bitcoin devotees have been donating small amounts of bitcoin (BTC) to the Genesis Block as a tribute to Satoshi Nakamoto. This is seen as a kind of sacrifice because once a coin is moved into the Genesis Block, it can never be moved again‚Äîsort of like throwing a quarter into a fountain. Bitcoin is a type of cryptocurrency, which is based on the peer-to-peer electronic cash system developed by Satoshi Nakamoto. Bitcoin refers to the system and concept of the trading platform and "bitcoin"‚Äîsmall "b"‚Äîrefers to the virtual coinage that is traded. There are no actual coins, thus the "bit"‚Äîor binary digit, the most basic unit of data in computing‚Äîbefore "coin."In the world of digital currency, blocks are files where data about the Bitcoin network and its transactions are permanently recorded. Each time a block is completed‚Äîthat is, filled with bitcoin transactions‚Äîit gives way to the next block in the blockchain. The only way to release new cryptocurrency into circulation is through mining. So, to "mine bitcoin" is to "mint currency."Like gold, Bitcoin cannot be created arbitrarily. Gold must be mined out of the ground, and BTC must be mined via digital means. Moreover, Bitcoin's founder stipulated that, like gold, the supply of bitcoin should be limited and finite. Only 21 million BTC can be mined in total. When miners have unlocked this many bitcoin, then the planet's supply will be tapped out, unless someone changes Bitcoin's protocol to allow for a larger supply. Mysteries of the Genesis BlockBeginning with the fact that the name, "Satoshi Nakamoto," itself is a pseudonym, the Genesis Block and the founding of Bitcoin remains riddled with mystery. Shortly after the launch of Bitcoin, the person called "Satoshi Nakamoto" vanished from the face of the earth, leaving barely a trace. This auspicious event paved the way for the continuous enigma surrounding what fans lovingly call "the Block." The First 50 BTC Could Not be SpenThe Genesis Block's beginnings were shrouded in the debate about a fine point of its creation: Was the code that rendered the Genesis Block effectively untradeable an intention or a mistake on the part of Nakamoto? Although the Genesis Block points to a web address‚Äîwritten into the Genesis Block's code‚Äîthat link displayed an error message when activated. The system could not find the first 50-BTC transaction in its database, and the spending transaction was rejected. So, the Genesis Block's transaction is not considered as a "real transaction" by the original Bitcoin client. But Why? Did Nakamoto mean for the first bitcoin to be non-tradeable? Or, was it a mistake? This became the subject of much debate among Bitcoin fans and insiders. Because of the precision of this developer, however, most believe that it was hardly an error. Nakamoto likely wrote the code for the Genesis Block exactly the way he wanted it. We just will never know why, as the quirk was not discovered until after Nakamoto disappeared. Current versions of the Bitcoin system handle the block/transaction databases differently from the original system, so the Genesis Bock's transaction is now just a weird special case in the codeAnother puzzling aspect of the Genesis Block is the secret message that Nakamoto instilled within the Block's raw data: "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks."vAlthough Nakamoto never commented on the meaning of this text, most believe that it serves as a mission statement for Bitcoin itself. The text is a headline for an article in the January 3, 2009 edition of The [London] Times about the British government's failure to stimulate the economy following the 2007‚Äì08 financial crisis. Nakamoto famously hated the idea of too-big-to-fail financial institutions and wanted Bitcoin to be different in that regard. Most people think that Nakamoto's reference to the article in the Genesis Block's code was a hint as to how Bitcoin is different from the big investment banks that needed government bailouts in 2008.Bitcoin cannot be bailed out because its process eliminates the middleman; there is no third-party, no corporate entity to go between BTC and the consumer. The Bitcoin network checks and double-checks itself continuously via complex mathematical problems that are first resolved by computers, then by human bitcoin miners. One cannot proceed with any bitcoin trade until the math puzzle is validated. Another failsafe is that, because all transactions are stored forever, the actions of miners can always be traced, which makes it impossible to hide any evidence of wrongdoing. In November 2013, early protegees of Nakamoto formed the Satoshi Nakamoto Institute (SNI) to educate the public about the history and vision of Bitcoin‚Äôs creation. Among other interesting details, the SNI houses one of the biggest remnants of Nakamoto‚Äôs online existence: An extensive list of forum posts, broken into subject categories, that the Bitcoin creator penned while he still worked on the project.Perhaps the true gift of the Genesis Block, however, is its legacy of accountability, integrity, and transparency‚Äîqualities that the financial services sector is painfully learning to acquire.35 unique frames created individually in illustrator and compiled into GIF animation. 1091x1200px, 44.8MB

name: D.CHOTOMY
description: There is a huge gap between the turbo-evolution that is characterizing this historical time and the imminent crisis that affects the absolute values that should shape our society. More and more often I feel like the concept of "truth" is becoming an empty container ready to be filled with disposable doctrines, invigorated by traditional media and its need of conversion. We are observing incredible innovations and developments, new economic systems, the recovering of the conquest of space and an overall behavioral shift towards eco-sustainable dynamics but yet we are still dealing with apparent basic concepts such as racial discrimination, social injustice and the disbelief towards the leading institutions. The fact that existence is a sinuous flux composed by the iterations between 2 opposite poles has never been so clear. This artwork doesn't have the purpose to communicate a political statement but is limited to highlighting the spasmodic dichotomy that envelopes our everyday reality.

name: SiddhƒÅrtha Gautama
description: SiddhƒÅrtha Gautama or simply the Buddha, was a monk, mendicant, sage, philosopher, teacher and religious leader on whose teachings Buddhism was founded. Gautama is the primary figure in Buddhism. He is believed by Buddhists to be an enlightened teacher who attained full Buddhahood and shared his insights to help sentient beings end rebirth and suffering. Accounts of his life, discourses and monastic rules are believed by Buddhists to have been summarized after his death and memorized by his followers. The Four Noble Truths: that suffering is an ingrained part of existence; that the origin of suffering is craving for sensuality, acquisition of identity, and fear of annihilation; that suffering can be ended; and that following the Noble Eightfold Path is the means to accomplish this; The Noble Eightfold Path: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right concentration; Dependent origination: the mind creates suffering as a natural product of a complex process.

name: SAGE Anomaly Redux
description: The first known anomaly from the SAGE computer briefly appeared at MIT on July 8, 1957. The Semi-Automatic Ground Environment was built to monitor for and launch weapons at Russian bombers attempting to drop nuclear bombs. The Air Force Technicians saw a strange image briefly form on their oscilloscopes. This time it was written off as a non-reproducible hardware anomaly. But there was some sort of mind-numbing distortion in this artificial intelligence generated reproduction of the event.Appeared at CADAF Miami 2019  https://cadaf.art/artists/bard-ionson Proceeds will be used to pay for entry to CADAF Paris and NYC 2020Historical image from public domain at National Archives 342-B-03-014-12-157480AC box 130.Caption: These Air Force technicians are watching scopes of the SAGE (Semi-Automatic Ground Environment) system, at the Massachusetts Instituted of Technology. SAGE will not make the ground controllers job any easier, rather it will let him handle a larger segment of the battle at one time.

name: A future you would actually like to live in
description: Not content to accept the dictates of a tomorrow ruled by authoritarian states, rapacious corporations, and a despoiled biosphere, solarpunk is an eco-futurist movement which tries to think our way out of catastrophe by imagining a future most people would actually like to live in, instead of ones we should be trying to avoid; a future characterized by a reconciliation between humanity and nature, where technology is utilized for human-centric and eco-centric ends, and where a society driven by hierarchy and competition has given way to one organized on the basis of freedom, equality, and cooperation. Its purpose is to serve as a compelling counter-narrative to the material and ideational conditions which keep us trapped in an authoritarian and ecocidal world where, as Margaret Thatcher put it, ‚Äúthere is no alternative‚Äù.From ‚ÄòWhat is Solarpunk?‚Äô by Connor Owens.Artwork was created using https://artbreeder.comArtbreeder app was created by Joel Simon https://www.joelsimon.net/

name: Moo
description: This is an image taken from my children's book "The Mirror," published by Harbinger House in 1989.  It was created on a Macintosh computer using "PixelPaint," the primary precursor of Photoshop.  This was in the day of 8-bit color, which limited me to a total of 256 colors.  There was no such thing as anti-aliasing, which is why the image has "jaggies," that I chose to emphasize rather than try to obscure.  In the book, two groups of very small beings--the Moos and the Foos--deal with prejudice fomented by General Foo, who is intent on building a wall.I have increased the resolution and size of the image.  The original digital files were lost long ago, so this image was taken from a scan of a copy of the book I once gave to a nephew."The Mirror" is widely recognized as the first ever children's book created in color on a computer to reach publication.For that reason and for others, the book and this digital image are a treasure and... SuperRare!

name: WindWalkr

name: What Child Is This
description: Since I was a child, I'd always been pulled in by paintings depicting the Madonna and Child. Long ago, I promised myself that I'd take a stab at religious motifs when my skill could only pose a compliment to the subject. This painting is based on a french postcard from the turn of the century. It was the practice of many photographers at the time to hire prostitutes for these commercial photographs. Given that, I wondered if this was indeed the woman's child. The closeness seems too natural to be staged. And did the child grow up knowing his father or had he been forsaken?Created on custom software programmed by the artist, using Processing and Java. Resolution: 16K x 24K. This painting required the artist to make 2,239 changes to 165 variables over the course of 12 man hours and consists of 148 layers consisting of 1,331,567 unique vector shapes and 54 different colors.

name: Incomplete Falling Trees - Part 3/3
description: This small series of Incomplete Falling Trees, fully coded in Processing, is dedicated to G√∂del's First Incompleteness Theorem, which roughly claims that 'there are truths that cannot be formally proved' (the presice statement in inscribed in the artwork itself).   G√∂del brilliant proof rests on a self-referencing formula G that speaks about itself and says 'G is not provable in any consistent formal system'. The sentence is true but unprovable.Also this artwork is self-referencing, since its generating code is graven into the artwork itself. The artwork's DNA is part of the artwork generated with the DNA. The artwork is naked, it has no hidden secret. You can use the printed code and generate precisely the same artwork, or almost. Since the code uses randomness, the outcome will be most likely slightly different. Incomplete Falling Trees is in fact a generating machine of Incomplete Falling Trees.

name: 1231_05.21.2012_9.2minutes_17:32
description: The Continuous Work Drawings (Double Dip), a series of 1500 digital drawings began as a way to think about the relationship of time spent doing other tasks during the day when I rather be making art. I wondered if it was possible to do both, make art and work at the same time, to double dip in a way. Each drawing was created through a computer program that tracked my cursor while quickly retouching E-commerce photos at work. Movements of my stylus on the tablet were recorded as simple continuous single pixel lines. The title refers to the drawing number, date created, how long it took to finish, and the time of day.

name: Cosmic Girl
description: In an extremely delicate and light in a way that seems not to be of this world, we can observe this graceful entity in space, in an ethereal pose, holding the light of a new knowledge, Ethereum."Cosmic Girl' is one of my favorite types of artwork I love creating, where I can make the atmosphere being felt as a whole while the focus is usually in a pictorial style, nevertheless the protagonist blends with its surroundings instead of being separated from them. The mask and aura of the protagonist has vibes of a Valkyrie. In Norse mythology, a valkyrie is one of a host of female figures who choose those who may die in battle and those who may live. In 'Cosmic Girl', I wanted to add elements of a powerful ethereal creature, elegant, mysterious, graceful and last but not least, the entity that seems to either create something or hold an important item. We can see the Ethereum shape. Our cosmic entity, either has created this out of her own energy, or she simply holds it. Perhaps, both. Seems that this has happened some time ago... when the knowledge of Ethereum was given to one human mind. Becomes quite a clear indication that there is a connection between the light radiation from the object which floats in her hand, and the light that is inside her, the light which animates her whole being.  While her entire posture is usually how I was able to add grace to her being, it is the details in her body what allowed me to gift my protagonist with a divine aura. The golden lines, subtle abs, feminine curves and such. Hope you enjoyed 'Cosmic Girl' :)

name: March 2020 - #5
description: March 2020 - #5 emerged from experimenting with media, material, and process. In this work Garet focuses on the properties of photography combined with repurposing discarded utilities, exploring technological malfunction, and found media to create the work. Garet applied transformative techniques, both tactile-analog and digital, that puts to test and transcends the sole nature of the source materials. The genesis of the work commenced by orchestrating different arrangements between the emission of film‚Äôs celluloid onto a projection screen, and a live feed of video connected to the computer for processing and feeding back imagery to the screen composing the work in real time. Garet then captured the combined output as an end result. This artwork was first exhibited at Renaissance 2.0 2.0 curated by Eleonora Brizi / Breezy Art Gallery: @eleonora.brizi The token is paired with a unique print on Hahnemuhle paper. In the secondary market, the token and the print will exist separately from each other. -- Material details: Archival Pigment Print; Hahnemuhle Photo Rag Baryta 315 gr., 100% Cotton, high-gloss finish. Framed in Italy. Size: 38,5 x 53,5 x 2 cm; 15 x 21 inches -- UNIQUE

name: Android Plaza - Distorted President
description: Distorted President captures Donald Trump on a recent visit to the UK. This flitting moment in history captures Trump in a digital broken orbit, caught forever in a timeless glitch of his own self importance.Harman's Android Plaza is a collection of digital artworks using a specially formulated algorithm. Within the corruption of the digital image, there is a breaking up of the information, which leaves the viewer to interpret the space between abstraction and figuration. He then digitally paints elements of the composition referencing Richter whilst the mangled figuration echoes Francis Bacon and Frank Auerbach.Harman is recognised as one of the leading UK's leading digital artists.

name: The Watcher (Clown Cloud #1)
description: This work is part of my series ‚ÄúNew beginnings, old endings, secrets secreting" where I use the Playform GAN to explore alternative methods of art creation and digital outsourcing. I use my past work "Color, Balance", as a data set to train the machine in my paintings‚Äô style. I then feed the network specific portraits I find online.The result of this process provides the base for new paintings I further alter in Photoshop.  Works are given life and animated in After Effects. When a neural network produces images, computer scientists often refer to them as ‚Äòdreams‚Äô due to their soft surreal-like quality. Considered a stepping stone in the search for artificial intelligence, hopes and fears surrounding these technologies act like barnacles on a ship‚Äîattaching themselves to ideas larger than any individual advance. Will AI create a new digital revolution freeing people of menial tasks or bring the end of humanity itself? The subject prompts consideration of my dreams and nightmares; real and imagined, small and large, wholesome, and vapid. I pair each work with a specific hope or fear of my own. Still images from this series were part of the exhibition "A Dream Within a Dream," organized by Playform Studio. Curated by Jessica Davidson, the show focuses on artists who use the Playform GAN in the process of creating their work.  Due to the COVID-19 pandemic the exhibition was presented online through Artsy in October, 2020. I first presented my series "New beginnings, old endings, secrets secreting" at RISE (NYC) in 2019 as part of the panel discussion "ARTificial Intelligence" organized by Eleonora Brizi.

name: Falcata
description: Acacia falcata, commonly known as sickle wattle and by other vernacular names including sally, is a perennial shrub or tree native to eastern Australia, which reaches five metres in height and has cream flowers in early winter. It gets its common and scientific name for its sickle-shaped leaves. Hardy and adaptable to cultivation, it is used in regeneration of bushland.Australian indigenous people use the bark to make a liniment for treating ailments of the skin. A. falcata is excellent for stabilizing barren sand. The bark is important in the tanning industry.The 1889 book 'The Useful Native Plants of Australia‚Äô records that common names included "Hickory" and "Sally" and that Indigenous Australians of the Cumberland and Camden areas of New South Wales referred to it as "Weetjellan" It also notes that "This bark, which contains much tannin, was used by the aboriginals of the counties of Cumberland and Camden to stupefy fish, and to make embrocations for the cure of cutaneous diseases." Psychoactive plant, but less than 0.02% alkaloids

name: Colorfall
description: If less is more, how do we do more with less? Colorfall is part of a minimalist series focused around colors, geometric shapes, and shadows. Its name is meant to trick the viewer into thinking for themselves and not taking anything for granted just because something is presented that way to them. Nothing in the piece is suggesting that something is falling especially not the colors, on the contrary, the colors are the primary support in the rising of the capsule center shape. This piece represents movement, using shadows and color gradients to showcase a geometric shape moving vertically in space supported by a white ring that the capsule seems to be passing through. It's completed by a white frame around the edges to draw the viewer's attention into the composition, apart from the bottom where the frame is covered by the color trails suggesting the capsule moving into the composition and taking center stage, hence moving in.

name: Kozachok's Inferno: 4th Circle of Hell: GREED
description: What is going on here?In the fourth circle of Kozachok's Inferno, we find the realm of Greed. The people who lived with an extreme or excessive desire for resources, especially for property such as money, real estate, and other symbols of wealth, obtained in numerous immoral ways, are now residing here, receiving exactly what they wanted constantly. Except, as there was no satisfied appetite in their greed, the same way there is no end to how much they still receive... constantly. In a place somewhat similar to the Limbo, we see restless people trying to find a minute of peace, however it is impossible to do so, since in this circle of hell, the sky is constantly 'raining' with one of the many objects we can see in this artwork.Sometimes it is raining with tons and tons of golden ingots (bars), hitting them painfully without being able to die. Other times, there are storms and hurricanes made out of paper money, again causing them to be restless. A feeling of sleep deprivation is constantly present, but they cannot rest as they are always disturbed by the 'income' of more riches. Sometimes fancy cars, vaults, luxurious appliances and other items, often and randomly fall from the sky hitting those who do not constantly watch out.The ones residing here, cannot feel hunger or thirst, but they can feel sleepiness, sleep deprivation, tiredness, pain, fear etc. There are numerous thin rivers of blood, symbolizing the price paid by other people for the riches of the ones in this circle.In a life where the desire to obtain more and more was ever present, including stealing the desires and hopes of other people, now in this circle of Greed, these people continue to obtain constantly what they wished for. And they will keep getting more and more 'riches' for an eternity.
tags: kozachok inferno 4th circle hell green dante drawing money gold ingots blood

By combining one of the original human creative outlets, painting, and advanced math with new technologies, a multitude of mages, seers, shamans and sages has been born. This is a creation built on a lifetime of Lee‚Äôs creations at the easel. B√•rd used over 250 Lee paintings to train a machine learning / artificial intelligence system and used his own creative skills to perfect the output of the software and to curate results. Lee then worked to identify the best of the generated images and used his digital painting skills and immense creativity to improve on what B√•rd produced. The goal was to expand the creative palette like a hallucinatory dream. Controlled by B√•rd with training selections, the AI produced a googleplex of possible random outcomes. Lawrence and B√•rd have hand-selected the best of each production run from the machine, and Lawrence has worked to unearth these new shamans and the landscapes they inhabit by enhancing them further and augmenting their otherworldly qualities in an attempt to better understand their roots and to release their powers. The winning bidder will have the option to redeem an exclusive 1 of 1 , 10" X 10" inch print valued at $250 created by Lawrence in his Arizona atelier. Coupon code will expire after two months if not redeemed.

name: Reflection
description: This is a one of a kind. Here is the creative process, which took hundreds of hours:First I had the inspiration for the above image and a few others which I had to create. Then I gathered a team of 2 photographers (plus myself), and 6 beautiful models. All of them are good friends, and they all agreed to participate in the project at no cost. We all traveled from northern Mexico to one of the worlds most exquisite beaches, in Cancun. I chose the model for this particular project, and we scouted the location. On the next day, we woke up before the Sun came up so that we would be ready at the place (actually inside the sea) when dawn happened, to capture the model being illuminated with the first rays of light. We photographed her, gorgeously nude, and took back home some awesome images. From a selection of photos, I then created an oil painting, with emphasis to capture the delicacy of the young woman and the deep blue of the surroundings. I then professionally photographed the painting, and worked digitally on the image, with Photoshop. I ran it through several filters and effects, some automatic and some manual, to get the impressionistic look I wanted; giving it the last little touches so that the most essential features, such as her face and hand, would be more realistic, while some of the rest would be almost lost. The image is in high resolution. That‚Äôs it!This is a unique, SuperRare work of art, a 1 of 1 piece which went through all the above process, with the hope that you could take home some of the warmth and beauty of the beautiful young woman, and some of the freshness and energy of the Caribbean Sea.

name: PumpAnon
description: Lifted from the popular Deplorables series, this artwork features an engraved portrait of Anon, behind bespoke typography. The Deplorables are the first legitimate banknote designs in the crypto space - both as NFTs and physical paper wallets. Anon is featured on the rarest of the series, and is also the most sought after. Unlike the original series, this high resolution, 600 dpi artwork allows the collector to view the engraving up close - every dot, dash and line. Engraved portraiture is a lost art form; it is only used with consistency in banknote manufacture. This single edition not only revives this rarely seen form of portraiture, but uses it to showcase a subject matter that would never be seen on money - until now!

name: Water Lilies after Claude Monet
description: I created this piece upon studying "Water Lilies," painted in oil on canvas by Claude Monet in 1906. Only the second in the series, I challenged myself to make any given close-up a dynamic abstraction. On the macro, I wished to impress my own palette upon the landscape while maintaining the figure ground relationships that Monet created between lilies, water, and reflections of sky and treeline on top of the water. Resolution: 15K x 14.5K // Approximate size on a 300 PPI retina screen: 1.27 meter x 1.22 meter or 4.16 feet x 4 feet. Made with Processing.org and Java. I visited, studied, sketched, made notes from, and and drew inspiration from photographed works at The Art Institute of Chicago. This research allowed me to create digitally rendered master copies after the works in Gallery 243, also known as The Monet Room. The master copy is a tradition in art in which a student artist creates a copy from a masterpiece in order to analyze and learn from the work. I create master copies in order to train myself to use the custom graphics software I've programmed, in addition to spurring the building of tools especially to meet the challenge of creating analogs to particular techniques. I've designed my software to leverage algorithms with my own human input. I build paintings layer by layer, making choices regarding color, shape, form, and how the algorithms I've written should interact at any particular time. The result is my ability to communicate in color and pattern in ways I long understood but which are too complex, time consuming, or cost prohibitive for my hand and materials to manifest physically with traditional methods. Total unique vector shapes: 1,243,070. verticies: 2,056,112. ellipses: 509,426. quad: 10,585. rectangles: 44,711. triangle: 16. beziers: 15,605. line: 662,727. colors used: 309.layers: 118.

name: SuperRare network / Circle layout
description: At 11:20:48 PM (UTC) of April 5th, 2018, the first piece was tokenized on SuperRare. It is "AI Generated Nude Portrait #1" by Robbie Barrat. About 30 minutes later (precisely at 11:50:12 PM), Artnome (Jason Bailey) bought the artwork for 0.46Œû ($176 at that time). Recently, Artnome accepted a bid of 75.0Œû ($13,265) from CuriousNFTs. Since today is the second birthday of SuperRare, I decided to generate this small series with four networks. Using SuperRare data until today, I built a buyer/creator network where the nodes of the network are the active users of SuperRare (those that made at least one sale, or at least one purchase, or that created at least one piece of art), and the links between nodes are drawn as follows. Suppose there is a sale from seller A to buyer B of a token T, where C is the artist that created artwork T. Then, I add an undirected link between B (the buyer) and C (the creator) to the network. The added link represents an endorsement of buyer B to artist C. The resulting graph contains 605 nodes and 4894 edges. The graph has been generated using ggraph library of R in four different layouts (random, circle, sphere and Sugiyama) and exported is high resolution SVG. All networks are available also in black color on white background upon request.

name: Politics of Creation
description: Let‚Äôs divide social anarchist practice into two rough families of approaches: combat anarchism and venture anarchism. Combat anarchism refers to acts of insurrection and struggle, typically mass insurrection and class struggle. Venture anarchism refers to acts of exodus and creation, typically exodus from the dominant system by way of living off-grid or adopting an anti-systemic lifestyle, and creation in the form of building non-hierarchical settlements or enterprises, or artistic and technological creations.Both are necessary. But successful action means knowing how much of one or the other to employ in a given situation. In the last few decades, anarchists have perhaps placed too much focus on what‚Äôs wrong we the current world we‚Äôre fighting against (for understandable reasons), and not enough on the kind of world we‚Äôd like to replace it with. In other words, we‚Äôve had too much combat anarchism and not enough venture anarchism. We need to appeal to people with discourse and optics which stress the positive features of the alternatives we want to build, emphasizing the values of caring, vitality, cooperation, and creativity, and tone down (without dispensing with) the discourse and optics of revolt, struggle, attack, and negation. To repeat, we need both, but as of now, we need to alter the balance to favour the politics of creation.From ‚ÄòSocial Anarchist Futures‚Äô by Connor Owens.Artwork was created using https://artbreeder.com Artbreeder app was created by Joel Simon https://www.joelsimon.net/

name: Eyck Can!
description: This artwork uses Jan Van Eyck‚Äôs ‚ÄúPortrait of a Man in a Red Turban‚Äù (c. 1433) which has been largely speculated to be a self portrait due to the direct and confrontational gaze of the man.  The original frame survives and although autographing paintings in the early 15th century was not common the original frame has the inscription at the bottom AIC IXH XAN which is a play of words with the painter‚Äôs last name that reads ‚ÄúI do as I can‚Äù. A similar motto appears in most of his paintings and its believed that it was done to signal he was challenging his predecessors as well as his contemporaries with his work and skill. The original painting has been manipulated to imply that competition in modern times would be greater hence the dramatically oversized red turban. Tones have been enhanced and the artwork has been plastified for stylistic purposes.

name: Rare Digital Art v Physical Art
description: I drew this comic as a satire to point out the remarkable advances in rare digital art over the past few years. Those active in the crypto space might even recognize a few crypto-art opinion leaders here. For this particular cartoon, I also decided to make rare digital art specifically about rare digital art as a fun (and slightly) educational piece. In the beginning there was just physical art. This, of course, is creative work that exists as a tangible unique object or experience in some form. Then with the dawn of computers and the Internet, came digital art. This led to droves of physical artwork--both old and new--becoming electronically scanned, digitized, and almost instantly available for viewing (and copying) around the globe. Those things alone are radical advances in arts development. Yet it does not stop there. With new innovations in blockchain technology came something called rare digital art. The art world will never be the same. What is rare digital art? It is non-physical creative work existing in electronic format that is made in a limited supply and running on top of cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin and Ethereum. At all hours of the day, a person anywhere in the world can buy rare digital art with cryptocurrency and have proof of ownership as well as proof of the art's digital scarcity. How the times have changed right underneath our artsy noses. One could almost smell it... almost. Woah!

name: Hallways Scenes For Things To Regret
description: If you‚Äôre familiar with Interpol‚Äôs track ¬´¬†Rest My Chemistry¬†¬ª you might recognize where that title comes from. It‚Äôs no secret that a lot of my artworks are inspired by songs and this is a really special one to me. I‚Äôve been referring to this track several times throughout my creative journey, naming pieces after some of its lyrics as a way to remind me to celebrate and be grateful for each year of sobriety. So naturally, for my 6th year, I‚Äôve sticked to this tradition and created ¬´¬†Hallways Scenes For Things to Regret¬†¬ª, a complex yet bright piece of work. See it as some sort of battle between dusk and dawn. Sobriety is a rollercoaster, it‚Äôs disturbing, painful, but also beautiful and enlightening. These are all feelings I wanted to convey for my first drop. It‚Äôs me, and it‚Äôs special. My creative journey had a huge impact on sticking to sobriety. It taught me so much. Patience, Passion, Love, Resilience... And I‚Äôm so grateful to be able to share it with you today. Overall, I feel like this artwork sums up a lot about finding peace through chaos. Hope you‚Äôll enjoy as much as I do.

name: When Good Men Do Nothing The Evil Triumphs
description: Whilst men are linked together, they easily and speedily communicate the alarm of any evil design. They are enabled to fathom it with common counsel, and to oppose it with united strength. Whereas, when they lie dispersed, without concert, order, or discipline, communication is uncertain, counsel difficult, and resistance impracticable. Where men are not acquainted with each other‚Äôs principles, nor experienced in each other‚Äôs talents, nor at all practiced in their mutual habitudes and dispositions by joint efforts in business; no personal confidence, no friendship, no common interest, subsisting among them; it is evidently impossible that they can act a public part with uniformity, perseverance, or efficacy. In a connection, the most inconsiderable man, by adding to the weight of the whole, has his value, and his use; out of it, the greatest talents are wholly unserviceable to the public. No man, who is not inflamed by vain-glory into enthusiasm, can flatter himself that his single, unsupported, desultory, unsystematic endeavors, are of power to defeat the subtle designs and united cabals of ambitious citizens. When bad men combine, the good must associate; else they will fall, one by one, an unpitied sacrifice in a contemptible struggle.‚Äì Edmund Burke, Thoughts on the Cause of the Present Discontents 82-83 (1770) in: Select Works of Edmund Burke, vol. 1, p. 146 (Liberty Fund ed. 1999).‚Äï‚ÄúThe only thing necessary for the triumph of evil is for good men to do nothing.‚Äù

name: The Exposed Swan 1/3
description: Painting as a medium was and still is a way to create worlds and capture our imagination in a 2D space, but these paintings are more than just an image, there is a whole environment that lies beyond and we as the viewer could only imagine it, until now. In my work, I recreated The Threatened Swan by Jan Asselijn in 3D software to reveal the composition in never seen before perspectives and also revitalize the medium and have it refreshed by more contemporary techniques on creating images. The new perspectives give us the ability to learn more about the original and possibly even reveal things we were not aware of. These new angles can enrich our imagination further, and let us become even more immersed and connected with the original motive by Jan Asselijn.

description: This one took me quite some time.It was a bit difficult to finish, to be honest, as my vision for this piece would not be suppressed, and involved quite a bit more manual editing the filter output than I originally intended. But when I saw the partial output (Imagine cropping the "crystal" by 30% at each corner, leaving unfinished edges), I just couldn't leave it like that. So, I sat down, over 4 days in the evenings, and used GIMP to cut and paste small, tiny fragments from different places in the artwork to complete it, while hiding as much as possible that the new parts hadn't always been a part of the artwork.Oh, and I nearly forgot. This #cryptoartwork was made ENTIRELY from applying different art filters to... a blank GIMP canvas ! It's truly incredible what can be achieved when you extract and refine patterns, even when the starting point is just a single color !

name: Fail
description: The figure in this piece appears to be staring out directly at its audience, somehow capturing our attention and eye contact without any obvious markers to entice us. Instead of being met with a face to read and contemplate, we are faced with a blur of colour in a downward motion, making the figure appear heavy and burdened. This is further emphasised by the deep, cavernous red of the kinetic background.The figure, despite being absorbed within their own world, invites us in to get an intimate perspective of their experience. This is even more prevalent with the use of text which fills the background. When repeated, the text appears to mimic voices from the outer world as its meaning dissipates through semantic satiation. Chloe Diamond, curator at Mocda

They stalk more silently,And crouch on the limbs of trees,   And their descentUpon the bright backs of their preyMay take yearsIn a sovereign floating of joy.   And those that are hunted   Know this as their life,Their reward: to walkUnder such trees in full knowledge   Of what is in glory above them,   And to feel no fear,But acceptance, compliance.
